# Responsive Web Design

Over 60% of web traffic now comes from mobile devices. A page that looks great on a desktop but breaks on a phone has failed half its audience. **Responsive web design** means building pages that adapt their layout and styling to any screen size.

The three tools that make a page responsive are:
1. A flexible layout (Flexbox or Grid)
2. Fluid images (`max-width: 100%`)
3. **Media queries** — the CSS rule that applies styles only at certain screen widths

## Media Query Syntax

```css
/* Applies when the viewport is 768px wide or narrower */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .sidebar { display: none; }
  .hero h1  { font-size: 24px; }
}
```

A media query wraps a block of CSS rules. The rules inside only take effect when the condition is true. Everything outside applies always.

## Common Breakpoints

A **breakpoint** is the viewport width at which a layout changes. These are widely used values:

| Breakpoint | Width | Target |
|---|---|---|
| Mobile | `< 480px` | Phones |
| Small tablet | `< 640px` | Large phones |
| Tablet | `< 768px` | Tablets |
| Laptop | `< 1024px` | Small laptops |
| Desktop | `≥ 1024px` | Desktops |

## max-width vs min-width

```css
/* max-width: applies when screen is AT MOST this wide */
@media (max-width: 768px) { /* mobile styles */ }

/* min-width: applies when screen is AT LEAST this wide */
@media (min-width: 769px) { /* desktop styles */ }
```

## Combining Conditions

```css
/* Only tablets — 480px to 768px */
@media (min-width: 480px) and (max-width: 768px) {
  .grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }
}
```

## Other Media Features

```css
@media (orientation: portrait) { /* phone held upright */ }
@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) { /* dark mode */ }
@media print { /* when printing */ }
```

